{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":36280,"record_hash":"sha256:c2861e2c53b70a33adae88e065df09b1c2533ed053d0f05b1670ec0a229ad9c3","timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:50:09.410Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"status\":{\"[REDACTED:entropy]\":{\"completed\":\"No files edited.\\n\\n**Core Read**\\nThe current model is right: keep transcripts on the project target and attach only `gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>` references to other targets. The existing POC already does this for project records and explicit targets in [gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:101).\\n\\nGitButler `change-id` is the best code-level anchor, but it is not perfect. The code explicitly says change IDs are carried through GitButler rebases, but are not unique and may represent different content over time in [commit/mod.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-core/src/commit/mod.rs:20). Also beware synthetic change IDs for headerless commits: they are derived from commit SHA, so they are not durable across rewrites unless a real header is written.\\n\\n**Options**\\n| Option | Shape | Failure Modes | Footprint |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| Explicit-only target links | User/API writes session keys to `branch`, `change-id`, `commit`, or future PR/review target. No inference. | Missed links. User can attach to weak targets. No automatic survival through squash/uncommit/recommit. | Smallest. Mostly current POC plus UI/API affordance. |\\n| PR/branch finalization | At PR publish/open/update, ask user to attach recent sessions to the PR or source branch target. | Coarse. PR target does not exist in current GitMeta target enum, so either overload `branch:<review-id>` or add target type. Branch rename/recreate can drift. | Small useful next step for review use case. |\\n| Change-id primary | Attach confirmed sessions to `change-id:<id>` at commit/amend moments. Branch/PR views union sessions from reachable commits’ change IDs. | Duplicate/change-drifting IDs. Synthetic IDs are weak. Squash drops non-surviving change IDs unless unioned. Uncommit/recommit loses linkage. Plain Git may drop headers. | Moderate. Best GitButler-native durability. |\\n| Commit target + propagation | Attach to exact commit \n[TRUNCATED]\n calls/patch similarity. Persist only confirmed links. | Privacy surface, false positives, expensive, hard to explain. | Largest. Long-term only. |\\n\\n**Lifecycle Notes**\\nFor amend, rebase, and whole-commit move, `change-id` is the least invasive anchor because GitButler rewrites carry headers forward.\\n\\nSquash needs special handling. The current squash builds the new commit by cloning the bottom-most commit and replacing tree/message in [squash_commits.rs]([REDACTED:entropy].rs:103), so the surviving change ID may not be the user-selected “target” commit’s change ID. If change-id associations exist, squash should union all selected commits’ session sets into the resulting commit’s surviving change ID.\\n\\nMove hunks / move changes is not cleanly representable at change-id granularity. Copying source sessions to the destination may be helpful, but it can overstate provenance. Best early behavior: do not silently propagate, or ask/confirm and mark it as coarse later.\\n\\nUncommit/recommit breaks durable code identity. The uncommitted state has no stable shareable target. Keep the old change-id link as historical context, then ask or suggest on recommit.\\n\\nOperations outside GitButler cannot be made correct by lifecycle hooks alone. Treat them as “best effort”: read existing real change-id headers when present, but avoid silent writes based on synthetic IDs or file/time guesses.\\n\\n**Recommendation**\\nSmallest implementation footprint: **explicit-only associations**. It matches the current data model, avoids lifecycle propagation, and keeps false positives out.\\n\\nSmallest useful product step for review sharing: **attach sessions at PR/branch publish time**, preferably confirmed by the user. For deeper code provenance later, use **change-id primary associations** plus one centralized union helper for squash, while accepting that uncommit/recommit and outside-Git operations need confirmation rather than automatic truth.\"}},\"timed_out\":false}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:50:09.410Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}